<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="340" pageId="2" pageNumber="339" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[677,1210,1250,1707]" box="[677,822,1250,1276]" pageId="2" pageNumber="339">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[677,1210,1250,1707]" box="[677,800,1282,1308]" pageId="2" pageNumber="339">
<emphasis box="[677,800,1282,1308]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="339">Morphology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[677,1210,1250,1707]" lastBlockId="3.[113,647,1128,1707]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="340" pageId="2" pageNumber="339">
A thin (
<quantity box="[759,889,1312,1339]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="2" pageNumber="339" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="0.8">0.8-1.5 mm</quantity>
) crust covering about 
<quantity box="[1125,1192,1312,1339]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="339" unit="cm" value="10.0">10 cm</quantity>
<superScript attach="left" box="[1192,1202,1308,1327]" fontSize="8" pageId="2" pageNumber="339">2</superScript>
. The appearance in the field was described as “gelatinous-grey with blue streaks on microconulous surface”; on a photograph taken fresh after collection the sponge looked slimy black. In alcohol the consistency is leathery, the color is a light tan. The specimen photographed (
<figureCitation box="[1059,1133,1497,1523]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="3.[113,124,970,987]" captionTargetBox="[116,646,208,931]" captionTargetId="figure-4@3.[116,646,208,931]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIG. 1. — Amphinolana claudelevii n. gen. n. sp.; A, photomacrograph of surface with cortical plates (alcohol-preserved specimen); B, ground thick section, perpendicular to surface, showing cortex and aquiferous groove (contracted) supported by strands of tylostyles. Scale bars: A, 5 mm; B, 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5400186" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5400186/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="339">Fig.1A</figureCitation>
) is the alcohol-preserved 
<typeStatus box="[893,995,1527,1553]" pageId="2" pageNumber="339">holotype</typeStatus>
(USNM portion) with pore grooves closed. Under the stereo microscope, the surface shows characteristic polygonal fields corresponding to cortical plates of amphiasters separated by aquiferous grooves devoid of cortical spicules. The grooves are marked by a slight elevation (
<quantity box="[299,435,1128,1155]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" unit="mm" value="0.4" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.2">0.2-0.6 mm</quantity>
high) of the abutting plate margins; in life they open to at least 
<quantity box="[113,199,1189,1216]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
and may have appeared as “blue streaks”, as reported by the collectors.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5400186" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5400186" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5400186/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" startId="3.[113,124,970,987]" targetBox="[116,646,208,931]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,648,970,1073]" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">
FIG. 1. — 
<taxonomicName authority="Rützler &amp; Hooper, 2000" authorityName="Rützler &amp; Hooper" authorityYear="2000" box="[192,393,970,987]" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" genus="Amphinolana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="claudelevii" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[192,393,970,987]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Amphinolana claudelevii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[397,456,970,987]" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
n. sp.; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[515,528,970,987]" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">A</emphasis>
, photomacrograph of surface with cortical plates (alcohol-preserved specimen); 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[172,185,1013,1030]" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">B</emphasis>
, ground thick section, perpendicular to surface, showing cortex and aquiferous groove (contracted) supported by strands of tylostyles. Scale bars: A, 5 mm; B, 50 
<emphasis box="[544,554,1056,1073]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">µ</emphasis>
m.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,647,1128,1707]" lastBlockId="3.[677,1210,208,787]" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">
Tracts of spongin-bound tylostyles (100-200 
<emphasis box="[610,624,1251,1276]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">µ</emphasis>
m wide) radiate from the substrate toward the surface where they penetrate in places supporting the cortical plates on either side of the grooves (
<figureCitation box="[122,211,1374,1400]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="3.[113,124,970,987]" captionTargetBox="[116,646,208,931]" captionTargetId="figure-4@3.[116,646,208,931]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIG. 1. — Amphinolana claudelevii n. gen. n. sp.; A, photomacrograph of surface with cortical plates (alcohol-preserved specimen); B, ground thick section, perpendicular to surface, showing cortex and aquiferous groove (contracted) supported by strands of tylostyles. Scale bars: A, 5 mm; B, 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5400186" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5400186/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
). The cortex consists of a dense, 60- 100 µm thick top layer of tightly spongincemented amphinolasters, followed by a 250-300 µm fibrous zone (700 µm in the region of a groove), striation parallel to the sponge surface, devoid of spicules but rich in spongin and cells, presumably actinocytes and spongocytes. The choanosome is a 400-1100 µm thick and includes most cellular components, aquiferous canals, and abundant but scattered amphinolasters (spaced on average 25 µm apart) and much rarer spirasters (
<figureCitation box="[924,1013,209,235]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[114,124,787,804]" captionTargetBox="[118,1206,211,748]" captionTargetId="figure-421@4.[117,1206,201,749]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 2.— Amphinolana claudelevii n. gen.n. sp.; A, part of tylostyle with microscleres;B, modifications in tylostyle heads.Scale bars:10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5400188" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5400188/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Figs 2A</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[1026,1064,209,235]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="6.[114,125,1131,1148]" captionTargetBox="[114,1211,207,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-5@6.[119,1208,206,1098]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIG. 3. — Amphinolana claudelevii n. gen. n. sp.; A-E, amphinolasters in different stages of development; F, spiraster and head of amphinolaster; G, spirasters and enlarged details of amphinolasters. Scale bars: 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5400190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5400190/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">3G</figureCitation>
). A sponginrich base layer (25-50 µm) attaches the sponge crust to the substratum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[677,1210,208,787]" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">
The amphinolasters (
<figureCitation box="[899,983,301,327]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[114,124,787,804]" captionTargetBox="[118,1206,211,748]" captionTargetId="figure-421@4.[117,1206,201,749]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 2.— Amphinolana claudelevii n. gen.n. sp.; A, part of tylostyle with microscleres;B, modifications in tylostyle heads.Scale bars:10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5400188" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5400188/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Figs 2A</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[991,1005,301,327]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="6.[114,125,1131,1148]" captionTargetBox="[114,1211,207,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-5@6.[119,1208,206,1098]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIG. 3. — Amphinolana claudelevii n. gen. n. sp.; A-E, amphinolasters in different stages of development; F, spiraster and head of amphinolaster; G, spirasters and enlarged details of amphinolasters. Scale bars: 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5400190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5400190/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">3</figureCitation>
) start development as straight, slender, spiny rhabds with longer spines toward the ends of the shaft. Mature spicules have smooth or lumpy shafts (lumps are poorly developed spines) and two heads densely covered by bulbous or mammiform spines fused at the base. In transmitted light, the shafts show distinct axial canals; no such structures are seen in the spines. Most spines in fully developed amphinolasters are mucronate, some are connected by delicate siliceous ridges or bear thin secondary spines (
<figureCitation box="[684,823,637,664]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="6.[114,125,1131,1148]" captionTargetBox="[114,1211,207,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-5@6.[119,1208,206,1098]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIG. 3. — Amphinolana claudelevii n. gen. n. sp.; A-E, amphinolasters in different stages of development; F, spiraster and head of amphinolaster; G, spirasters and enlarged details of amphinolasters. Scale bars: 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5400190" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5400190/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Fig. 3A, F, G</figureCitation>
), possibly stages in the deposition of silica. Tylostyles are long, slender, gradually tapering toward the point, with inconspicuous oval heads; some heads are subterminal or show one or more constrictions (
<figureCitation box="[892,975,761,787]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[114,124,787,804]" captionTargetBox="[118,1206,211,748]" captionTargetId="figure-421@4.[117,1206,201,749]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 2.— Amphinolana claudelevii n. gen.n. sp.; A, part of tylostyle with microscleres;B, modifications in tylostyle heads.Scale bars:10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5400188" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5400188/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[677,1210,821,1277]" box="[677,899,821,848]" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">
<emphasis box="[677,899,821,848]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Spicule measurements</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[677,1210,821,1277]" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Measurements are ranges; means and standard errors are in parentheses. Tylostyles, length × width: 450-700 (578.0 ± 24.2) × 5.0-7.5 (6.3 ± 0.1) µm; tylostyle heads, length × width: 8.8- 15.0 (12.0 ± 0.7) × 6.3-10.0 (7.8 ± 0.3) µm. Mature amphinolasters, length × width (head) × width (shaft): 27.5-42.5 (39.0 ± 1.4) × 15.0-20.0 (16.8 ± 0.8) × 6.3-15.0 (8.5 ± 0.8) µm; immature amphinolasters (rays free, not yet cemented along their lengths), length × width (head) × width (shaft): 25.0-33.8 (30.9±1.1) × 5.0-12.5 (8.3 ± 0.9) × 1.3-5.0 (3.0 ± 0.4) µm. Spirasters (bent or double-bent spiny rhabds), length × width (n = 5): 8.8-12.5 × 1.0 µm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="342" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[677,1210,1312,1707]" box="[677,777,1312,1338]" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[677,1210,1312,1707]" lastBlockId="4.[114,647,852,1707]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="341" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rützler &amp; Hooper" authorityYear="2000" box="[677,950,1343,1369]" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" genus="Amphinolana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="claudelevii">
<emphasis box="[677,950,1343,1369]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">Amphinolana claudelevii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
stands out among the species in the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1867" box="[933,1125,1374,1400]" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" phylum="Porifera" rank="family">Placospongiidae</taxonomicName>
by the morphology and development of its cortical spicules and the simple complement of accessory microscleres which are absent in the cortex and canal walls. Five species are recognized in the only other genus, 
<emphasis box="[828,975,1527,1553]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="340">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1867" box="[828,971,1527,1553]" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" genus="Placospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="3" pageNumber="340" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">Placospongia</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
which share oval or bean-shaped cortical selenasters and are distinguished on the basis of their accessory microscleres (spirasters, spiny microrhabds, spherasters, spherules) and their location (cortex, canal walls), not by differences in cortical microscleres. These species include the genotype, 
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1867" authorityName="Gray. Anales" authorityYear="1867" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" genus="Placospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="4" pageNumber="341" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="melobesioides">
<emphasis box="[469,646,852,879]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="341">P. melobesioides</emphasis>
Gray, 1867
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Bowerbank, 1859)" baseAuthorityName="Bowerbank" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[270,647,883,909]" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" genus="Placospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="4" pageNumber="341" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="carinata">
<emphasis box="[270,398,883,908]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="341">P. carinata</emphasis>
(Bowerbank, 1859)
</taxonomicName>
(including 
<taxonomicName authority="Sollas, 1888" authorityName="Sollas" authorityYear="1888" box="[232,508,913,940]" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" genus="Placospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="4" pageNumber="341" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="intermedia">
<emphasis box="[232,370,913,940]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="341">P. intermedia</emphasis>
Sollas, 1888
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Thiele, 1900" authorityName="Thiele" authorityYear="1900" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" genus="Placospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="4" pageNumber="341" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="mixta">
<emphasis box="[562,646,913,938]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="341">P. mixta</emphasis>
Thiele, 1900
</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName authority="Boury-Esnault, 1973" authorityName="Boury-Esnault" authorityYear="1973" box="[286,642,944,971]" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" genus="Placospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="4" pageNumber="341" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="cristata">
<emphasis box="[286,392,944,969]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="341">P. cristata</emphasis>
Boury-Esnault, 1973
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hanitsch, 1895)" baseAuthorityName="Hanitsch" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[114,464,975,1001]" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" genus="Placospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="4" pageNumber="341" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="decorticans">
<emphasis box="[114,259,975,1001]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="341">P. decorticans</emphasis>
(Hanitsch, 1895)
</taxonomicName>
(incl. 
<taxonomicName authority="von Lendenfeld, 1894" authorityName="von Lendenfeld" authorityYear="1894" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" genus="Placospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="4" pageNumber="341" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="graeffei">
<emphasis box="[542,646,974,1000]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="341">P. graeffei</emphasis>
von Lendenfeld, 1894
</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Kirkpatrick, 1904" authorityName="Kirkpatrick" authorityYear="1904" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" genus="Placospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="4" pageNumber="341" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="labyrinthica">
<emphasis box="[434,592,1005,1032]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="341">P. labyrinthica</emphasis>
Kirkpatrick, 1904
</taxonomicName>
and are described in Vosmaer &amp; Vernhout (1902), Kirkpatrick (1903), and Boury-Esnault (1973). Only 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hanitsch" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[453,601,1097,1124]" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" genus="Placospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="4" pageNumber="341" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="decorticans">
<emphasis box="[453,601,1097,1124]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="341">P. decorticans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has distinctive selenasters, pronouncedly bean-shaped instead of ovoid, but the structure and development of these spicules are identical to their counterparts in the other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1867" box="[445,577,1221,1247]" class="Demospongiae" family="Placospongiidae" genus="Placospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="4" pageNumber="341" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[445,577,1221,1247]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="341">Placospongia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
